# Cursor Rules for Health Tracker Project

## Project Information
- **Repository**: https://github.com/bhumika121121/Health-Tracker.git
- **Main Branch**: main
- **Project Type**: Static HTML/CSS/JavaScript website

## Deployment Rules

### GitHub Actions Workflow
- **Workflow File**: `.github/workflows/deploy.yml`
- **Auto-deployment**: Automatically deploys to GitHub Pages when code is pushed to `main` branch
- **Deployment Path**: The `wellness/` directory is deployed as the static site
- **Workflow Triggers**: 
  - Automatic on push to `main` branch
  - Manual via workflow_dispatch
- **After pushing to GitHub**: The workflow will automatically run and deploy to GitHub Pages

### When deploying to GitHub:
1. **Always check Git status first** before making changes
2. **Commit messages should be descriptive** and follow this format:
   - `feat: [description]` for new features
   - `fix: [description]` for bug fixes
   - `update: [description]` for updates
   - `style: [description]` for styling changes
   - `docs: [description]` for documentation

3. **Before pushing to GitHub**:
   - Ensure all files are saved
   - Run `git status` to see what changed
   - Add files with `git add .` or specific files
   - Commit with a meaningful message
   - Push to main branch: `git push origin main`
   - The GitHub Actions workflow (deploy.yml) will automatically trigger and deploy

4. **GitHub Repository Details**:
   - Remote URL: https://github.com/bhumika121121/Health-Tracker.git
   - Default branch: main
   - Always push to main branch unless creating a feature branch
   - GitHub Pages will be automatically updated via the workflow

5. **File Structure**:
   - Main project files are in the `wellness/` directory
   - Root level contains configuration files (.gitignore, scripts, .github/workflows, etc.)
   - The `deploy.yml` workflow deploys the `wellness/` folder to GitHub Pages

6. **When user asks to deploy or push**:
   - Check if git is initialized
   - Verify remote is set correctly
   - Stage all changes
   - Create commit with descriptive message
   - Push to GitHub repository
   - Confirm successful push
   - Inform user that GitHub Actions will automatically deploy to GitHub Pages

7. **Never commit**:
   - Sensitive information (API keys, passwords)
   - Large binary files
   - Node modules (if added later)
   - Build artifacts unless necessary

## Code Style
- Use consistent indentation (spaces, not tabs)
- Comment complex logic
- Keep HTML semantic and accessible
- Use modern CSS (flexbox, grid)
- Follow JavaScript best practices

